05623nam a22008535i 9780812207286DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112008pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013948351  a(OCoLC)979741272  a97808122072867 a10.9783/97808122072862doi  a(DE-B1597)449512  a(OCoLC)811411235  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aSB457.8 ǂb .R85 2008eb 7aARC0080002bisacsh04a712.0917/671 aRuggles, D. Fairchild, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIslamic Gardens and Landscapes /cD. Fairchild Ruggles. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b28 color, 177 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPenn Studies in Landscape Architecture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. The Islamic Landscape -- t2. Making the Desert Bloom -- t3. The Science of Gardening -- t4. Organizing the Earth -- t5. Trees and Plants -- t6. Representations of Gardens and Landscape -- t7. Imaginary Gardens -- t8. The Garden as Paradise -- t9. The Here and Hereafter -- t10. A Garden in Landscape -- t11. Religion and Culture -- tList of Gardens and Sites -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"In the course of my research," writes D. Fairchild Ruggles, "I devoured Arabic agricultural manuals from the tenth through the fourteenth centuries. I love gardening, and in these texts I was able to enter the minds of agriculturalists and botanists of a thousand years ago who likewise believed it was important and interesting to record all the known ways of propagating olive trees, the various uses of rosemary, and how best to fertilize a garden bed."Western admirers have long seen the Islamic garden as an earthly reflection of the paradise said to await the faithful. However, such simplification, Ruggles contends, denies the sophistication and diversity of the art form. Islamic Gardens and Landscapes immerses the reader in the world of the architects of the great gardens of the Islamic world, from medieval Morocco to contemporary India.Just as Islamic culture is historically dense, sophisticated, and complex, so too is the history of its built landscapes. Islamic gardens began from the practical need to organize the surrounding space of human civilization, tame nature, enhance the earth's yield, and create a legible map on which to distribute natural resources. Ruggles follows the evolution of these early farming efforts to their aristocratic apex in famous formal gardens of the Alhambra in Spain and the Taj Mahal in Agra.Whether in a humble city home or a royal courtyard, the garden has several defining characteristics, which Ruggles discusses. Most notable is an enclosed space divided into four equal parts surrounding a central design element. The traditional Islamic garden is inwardly focused, usually surrounded by buildings or in the form of a courtyard. Water provides a counterpoint to the portioned green sections.Ranging across poetry, court documents, agronomy manuals, and early garden representations, and richly illustrated with pictures and site plans, Islamic Gardens and Landscapes is a book of impressive scope sure to interest scholars and enthusiasts alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aGardens, Persian. 0aIslamic gardens. 4aGarden History. 7aARCHITECTURE / Landscape.2bisacsh  aArchitecture.  aCultural Studies.  aFine Art.  aGarden History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Religionz978311041358808i